FOOT & MOUTH DISEASE - ALGERIA (04): SPREAD, VACCINATION, REQUEST FOR INFORMATION
*********************************************************************************
A ProMED-mail post
http://www.promedmail.org
ProMED-mail is a program of the
International Society for Infectious Diseases
http://www.isid.org

[1]
Date: 30-31 Jul 2014
Sources: Radio Algerienne http://www.radioalgerie.dz/news/fr/article/20140730/8605.html
La Depeche de Kabylie http://www.depechedekabylie.com/evenement/141219-trois-autres-a-tizi-ouzou.html
Le Temps d'Algerie http://www.letempsdz.com/content/view/128181/1/
[all in French, summ.]


According to the above 3 Algerian media sources, foot-and-mouth disease (FMD) outbreaks in cattle have, so far, been recorded within the following 8 provinces (wilayas): (in parentheses, their respective numbers as presented on the administrative map; see comment).

Batna (5), Bejaia (6), Bouira (10), Tizi-Ouzou (15), Setif (19), Constantine (25), Medea (26), Bordj Bou Arreridj (34).

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[All the 8 provinces mentioned above (out of a total of 48 provinces in Algeria) are located in the northern, fertile, populated regions of Algeria; Medea, the most western affected province, is located about 450 km (about 280 miles) from Algeria's western border, with Morocco. See map and data on the size/area (in sq km) of each province and its population, at http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Algeria#Provinces_and_districts. The numbering of the provinces is in Arabic alphabetical order.

Algeria reported on 27 Jul 2014 an outbreak in cattle in the province of Setif, indicating that serotyping was "pending". The serotyping should have been completed by now. An official follow-up report with the serotype identity and details on the additional outbreaks is anticipated to be submitted soon. - Mod.AS]

******
[2]
Date: Fri 1 Aug 2014
Source: El Watan (Algeria) [in French, transl. Mod.AB, summ., edited]
http://www.elwatan.com//actualite/fievre-aphteuse-les-eleveurs-crient-a-la-faillite-01-08-2014-266401_109.php


Six [apparently 8, according to data in item 1 above - Mod.AS] of Algeria's provinces are affected by FMD. Livestock owners complain and say they may go bankrupt, while the Ministry of Agriculture is launching preventive measures and pointing fingers at farmers accusing them of not reporting suspected cases in a timely manner, favoring thereby the spread of the disease.

In Bouira [wilaya/province], the authorities decided to close all livestock markets after the detection of a case last Wednesday [30 Jul 2014] in the city of Ain Turk, northwest of the capital of the province. This outbreak was reported following an introduction in the province of cattle purchased at livestock markets in the wilaya of Setif. "All necessary steps have been taken by us to prevent the spread of the viral disease," said the Director of Animal Health (DSA) of Bouira, Dr. Morseli Rachid, who also declared that a monitoring unit was immediately installed in his province.

In Medea [wilaya], the veterinary services urged farmers to take all necessary precautions to protect their animals from the dangerous virus, which was supposedly introduced into the region via diseased animals originating from neighboring wilayas. 8 cases were found last Sunday [27 Jul 2014] in 3 farms located in the town of Benchicao. 8 of the 11 examined cattle were immediately slaughtered and the offals and meat parts likely to carry the virus incinerated. Mohamed Slama, veterinary and department head at the DSA signals the urgency to implement the aforementioned measures.

"The main source of this epizootic are the owners of the 1st 75 registered bovine cases who hid their cattle when they noticed they were infected and threw the bodies," said Karim Boughanem, Director of Veterinary Services, Ministry of Agriculture and Rural Development. This highly contagious animal disease affects cattle, sheep and goats. But it is thought the virus currently in circulation in Algeria has a specific tropism to cattle. "Contamination of the Algerian livestock came initially from Tunisia to Daira Bir El Arch," he adds.

Since the contamination concerns, for now, an area of high concentration of cattle, this warning may result in serious economic constraints and declines in livestock prices. "Prices of cattle heads have fallen since the discovery of the 1st case. Farmers sell their cattle at any price for fear of losing a lot economically, and therefore the red meat market is experiencing a remarkable decline in prices, "said Mohamed Tahar Ramram, President of the section of red meat of the General Union of Algerian Traders and Artisans (UGCAA).

"This warning is a blow to farmers in the eastern region, as all livestock markets are preventively closed to limit the spread of the disease. Dr. Ramram is worried that some farmers do not adhere to the policy in place and this would undermine the efforts for combatting the disease presently underway. He added, "Thanks to the mobilization of the services concerned, between 110 and 115 farmers affected by the crisis have been supported." Unfortunately compensation of these farmers is still awaited.

[Byline: Amar Fedjkhi]

