******
[3]
Date: Fri 1 Aug 2014
Source: EU press release [edited]
http://europa.eu/rapid/midday-express.htm?locale=FR


Commission supplies emergency consignment of foot-and-mouth disease vaccine to Algeria and Tunisia
--------------------------------------------------------------------------------
The European Commission is sending, as an emergency response, a total of 1.1 million doses of foot-and-mouth disease (FMD) vaccines to the Algerian and Tunisian authorities, in support of the FMD control campaign carried out following the spread of a new strain of the virus. The European Commission is responding to a request from the UN's Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO) and the World Organisation for Animal Health (OIE) who asked for urgent assistance to supply a high quality vaccine for a vaccination campaign against the FMD epidemic due to the lack of available options to obtain in due time vaccines from other sources. The vaccine is formulated from the antigen stocks stored in the EU antigen bank. The shipment is due to be delivered within the next 2 weeks [by about 15 Aug 2014]. The vaccine will be used to immunise cattle, sheep and goats. The European Commission is supporting the eradication programme since this highly contagious viral disease affecting cloven-hoofed animals represents a threat to the EU's FMD free status and in particular to its Mediterranean Member States. The EU does not allow imports of live susceptible animals from Algeria and Tunisia or any of their products. Persons travelling from those countries to the EU are prohibited from bringing in their luggage any meat and milk products as they may harbour the virus.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>

[It seems that the European Commission authorities believe both Tunisia and Algeria to share the same FMDV strain. The Tunisian strain has been serotyped O and genotyped as FMDV "O/ME-SA/Ind-2001 lineage". This strain is known to have spread in recent years from the Indian sub-continent into West Eurasia and North Africa (Libya), and appears to be gaining pace. Since late 2013, further O/ME-SA/Ind-2001 outbreaks have been recognized in Saudi Arabia; and since early 2014 in the United Arab Emirates. In April 2014, this virus was reported from Tunisia, causing numerous outbreaks in cattle and small ruminants (sheep and goats), and spreading further west into Algeria (probably earlier than reported). According to their respective reports, all 3 Maghreb countries, Tunisia, Algeria and Morocco, have not experienced FMD outbreaks since 1999.

A useful update on the global FMD situation is available in the monthly "EUFMD Foot-and-Mouth Disease Situation Report" for June 2014, available at http://www.fao.org/fileadmin/user_upload/eufmd/docs/FMD_monthly_reports/JUNE2014_Final.pdf. It includes a detailed review on Tunisia, with map and graphic (pages 13, 14, 15). The guest editor indicated that "vaccine matching tests (are) needed" in relation to Tunisia (see table 7, page 16).

Both Tunisia and Algeria have reported mass vaccinations during 2014; it will be interesting to obtain information on the vaccine strains included and the protection conferred according to field observations.

Information on the vaccine strain included in the vaccines to be soon supplied by the European Commission to Tunisia and Algeria will be helpful.

Morocco deserves to take preventive measures against the virus circulating in the 2 other Maghreb countries. An article (in French) addressing this need is available at http://www.libe.ma/La-menace-de-fievre-aphteuse-plane-sur-le-cheptel-national_a52687.html. - Mod.AS

A HealthMap/ProMED-mail map can be accessed at: https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=2654821,67.]
